using System.Collections.Frozen;
using IRacingOverlay.Core.Cars;
using Geometry = System.Windows.Media.Geometry;

namespace IRacingOverlay.App.Cars;

/// <summary>
/// Monochrome vector marks for the standings manufacturer badge, as WPF path
/// geometry.
///
/// Source: the Simple Icons set (https://simpleicons.org), which publishes its
/// SVGs under CC0. Each mark is that project's single-path 24x24 glyph, so the
/// badge scales cleanly and takes its colour from the caller's Fill - the marks
/// carry no colour of their own. The underlying logos remain the manufacturers'
/// trademarks; they are used here only to identify the car a driver is in.
///
/// Every path is prefixed "F1" to select the nonzero fill rule. SVG defaults to
/// nonzero, WPF's mini-language defaults to even-odd - without the prefix any
/// mark with a hole in it (the BMW roundel, the Audi rings) renders inverted.
///
/// Not every make iRacing fields has a CC0 mark: Dallara, Ligier, Radical and
/// Ruf are absent upstream and fall back to the abbreviation chip (see
/// ManufacturerBadge). Mercedes was also absent, but its star is pure geometry
/// and is hand-authored below.
///
/// The extracted marks are generated from the upstream SVGs - re-extract rather
/// than hand-editing that path data.
/// </summary>
internal static class ManufacturerMarks
{
    private static readonly FrozenDictionary<Manufacturer, Geometry> Marks = CreateMarks();

    /// <summary>The mark for a make, or null when there is no artwork for it.</summary>
    public static Geometry? For(Manufacturer make) => Marks.GetValueOrDefault(make);

